  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Software validation checks that the software product satisfies or fits the intended use (high-level checking), i.e.,&#xD;
    the software meets the user requirements, not as specification artifacts or as needs of those who will operate the&#xD;
    software only; but, as the needs of all the stakeholders (such as users, operators, administrators, managers,&#xD;
    investors, etc.) [1]. First, the architect must validate the prioritized design goals against the stakeholder 's&#xD;
    expectations. Next, we need to validate the architectural decisions in meeting the non-functional requirements against&#xD;
    the stakeholder's expectations [2].&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>References&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    [1] En.wikipedia.org. (2018). Software verification and validation. [online] Available at:&#xD;
    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_verification_and_validation [Accessed 8 Apr. 2018].&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    [2] Michael, J., Riehle, R. and Shing, M. (2018). RIT Libraries: Off Campus Log-In to Library Resources. [online]&#xD;
    Ieeexplore.ieee.org.ezproxy.rit.edu. Available at: http://ieeexplore.ieee.org.ezproxy.rit.edu/document/5282319/&#xD;
    [Accessed 8 Apr. 2018].&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
